  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's a comprehensive overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive legal framework under Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Heavy criminal and civil penalties\n- Proactive enforcement by multiple agencies\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Harmonized regulatory standards across member states\n- Emphasis on customer due diligence\n- Enhanced cross-border cooperation mechanisms\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated risk-based regulatory approach\n- Strong financial intelligence unit\n- Extensive international collaboration\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more lenient regulations\n- Recent reforms increasing transparency\n- Strong banking secrecy traditions\n- Increasing international compliance pressures\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Strict governmental oversight\n- Significant criminal penalties\n- Growing emphasis on international standards\n\n6. Singapore\n- Stringent regulatory environment\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Severe criminal consequences\n- Attractive international financial compliance model\n\nCommon themes across jurisdictions:\n- Customer identification requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing\n- Increasing technological sophistication\n- Progressively stricter regulations\n\nEach approach reflects unique legal, cultural, and economic contexts.",
